posts.body:
Can we just take a minute and talk about how ridiculous this snapchat shit is? Don't get me wrong, I want to tie this bitch up and fuck her throat as much as the next guy. But let's take a step back and really analyze this shit.

I have no idea how much this girl charges people, but let's look at the history of camwhores for some reference. In this modern age it's worse than it's ever been. 10 years ago, if you wanted to be an internet thot, you usually had your own kind of shitty website, and at the very least took pictures with an actual god damn camera.

But this shit? Why is it suddenly now acceptable to make people pay money to have access to a fucking SNAPCHAT of all things? Who actually thinks "Why yes, I would love to pay $100 a month to receive shitty portrait mode photos taken by a shitty camera that I can only view once a day and for an arbitrary amount of time." At least something like this used to take some kind of effort, with good photographers, or at least real fucking equipment, like a real camera and a halfway decent lighting setup. But now, apparently it's just fine to take shitty half-assed blurry fucking pictures with a shitty phone camera. What the fuck happened?

I get it, this girl (and others like her) are cashing in on a very specific kind of niche, but are all of us so fucking desperate that we're complacent with this level of q

>>8bb104e1-e1b7-4e17-a9cb-10de0fb8ef8a
It depends on who ends up taking the pictures and editing the pictures. This one set in particular is my least favorite of hers because it's missing a lot of "natural" appearance. Whoever edited these pictures managed to completely remove all indications of unique identity in the texture of everyone's skin. 

Human skin is supposed to have lots of conflicting textures and colors. That kind of appearance is nowhere to be found in this set. Whoever edited this one opted for transforming it into a completely homogeneous, uniform texture in appearance. It just looks really fucking weird, like they're all made of plastic. It doesn't look natural at all. 

Compare the pictures from >>0f09a90e-060d-469a-9fa8-c67c071e597b to any number of sets Darshelle herself has released that aren't these. There's a noticeable difference in the overall appearance of her skin when compared to this one. I have no doubt that Darshelle's sets are given some heavy Photoshop treatment, but whoever does it manages to keep her from looking completely like a plastic doll. 

So as long as some moron isn't the one editing them, I would like the idea.

>>6aac5982-a965-4023-ab08-975ce0953827
I'm not that guy who's bitching, but I would expect that if there is any watermark, it's probably something silly like a single pixel or a single group of pixels at a specific color. This way the image can be easily identified by whomever (or whatever) put the watermark there, and would be completely invisible to people who don't know what to look for. 

Compression typically does nothing against a pixel watermark. They are usually placed in areas where even with the highest amount of compression, the watermark(s) remain unaffected. My understanding of this type of watermarking is it relies on color. Instead of compressing the images, what you could probably do is slightly alter them in Photoshop or GIMP. Bump up the contrast/brightness/whatever by 0.1% and that would probably be enough to throw off any pixel watermarks. If you want to be extra safe, you could probably play around with the color grading ever so slightly to ensure any watermark pixels would be far out of identifiable color range. This can be done quite easily with color curves in Photoshop. The pixel watermark in question would no longer have the same color, so it would most likely be unidentifiable by any software used to tag images like this. An insignificant adjustment like this would be preferable to compressing it by 5%. The file will still be the original resolution with no significant compression, and it's not like anybody who gets it for free would know the difference because they've never seen the original.

>>62b0c53e-2446-4ede-ba9a-6a8f904a0ce1
>how would reducing image resolution impact pixel watermarks? 
Probably wouldn't change them at all. They would still be in the same location, relative to the original resolution. I've played around with a few different "invisible watermarking" programs and all of them are more-or-less able to identify the image even after it's been heavily resized. I'm fairly certain color grading is the only way to throw them off.  
>I've also wondered if just releasing a slightly different image resolution could be used to identify people 
It could, but this depends entirely on the Patreon thot in question. I know awhile back Kayla was posting all of her sets on Patreon as shareable dropbox links. There was no "personalization" to the link, it was a single link that anybody with the link could use to download the set. From what I've heard, she started doing link expiries, so after X amount of time the dropbox link 404's. In any case where a link is shared en-masse, it's unlikely that any serious "copyright protection" measures will be taking place. In the case of a DM it's likely a very different story.

posts.subject: The Complete Fakku Set
posts.body:
This is an old set for sure, but it took her over a year to release all the bits and pieces to it and now it is finally complete. In 2018 she initially released the red slingkini pictures, but she teased a few where she was in a t-shirt and striped bikini, and a few more where she was just wearing the striped bikini by itself.  

A few months ago I managed to find the t-shirt bikini tease pictures in a satisfactory resolution, but those bikini-only pictures never saw the light of day. Until now. I decided to bite the bullet and drop $20 for the Fakku Bikini set she put up on Gumroad. I was expecting to see the same pictures I found a few months ago, but to my surprise it was all of the bikini pictures from this set, the ones she teased over a year ago.  

Kinda fucking absurd it took her over a year to release all of the bits and pieces to this, but it's finally complete. And I want to share it with y'all, as a gift for the leaks you have all given me.

posts.body: Hopefully this will quell any of the drama from you guys who think the shit on Gumroad is "the same" as what you already have. Those fuzzy ass waifu2x'd imgur compressed images you guys have are not the same as what's on Gumroad. You may have the same looking pictures but at least these ones aren't meant for ants. You're welcome.

>>ee87a9ee-1c59-4631-b876-c93132e994f5
Here's a MEGA link: https://mega.nz/#F!1boTVabD!2Vh6xzVbBhEPRy2-q4b2FA

But also, do what that other guy said. If you still have issues opening files after 10-15 minutes, check which ones are giving you problems. Zeronet can be finnicky sometimes and you'll have to directly open any images that are giving you problems, or outright tell Zeronet to delete the problem files so you can re-download them.

>>e0a71d75-bf48-4cc6-9a58-8679e5a7303a
And this is exactly why I didn't bother doing that. I have the space, I have the ability to upload them as I originally downloaded them, and this platform is more than capable of supporting it. 
>>4d1dfc56-1728-4744-82b8-0ab1860e3585
I get what you're saying but I'm never going to upload any pictures that have been altered like this. I will always upload them as the original files I downloaded. The reason being what I said above. There's no reason to. If you want to compress the pictures to save space on your own device then by all means, go right ahead. Don't assume huge files like this are uploaded because of gross incompetence, there's a reason people want to get the version that's as close as possible to the original. It's because it will absolutely, positively be the highest possible quality you can get for it. Whether it's a negligible difference or not doesn't matter, it's about the principle of having what is more-or-less "the original". You can go out and buy a replica of the Mona Lisa but it's not the same thing as if you were to actually own the original one.
